To illustrate structural causal models (SCMs) represented as directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) and the concept of interventions, let's create a few simple examples using TikZ. We'll represent different scenarios where intervening on a variable affects or does not affect another variable.

### Example 1: Simple DAG with Direct Causal Relationship

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]
    \node[circle, draw] (X) {X};
    \node[circle, draw, right of=X] (Y) {Y};

    \draw[->] (X) -- node[above] {$a$} (Y);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

In this example:
- \( X \) is a cause of \( Y \).
- The arrow from \( X \) to \( Y \) represents the causal effect \( a \).

### Example 2: Intervention on \( X \)

When we intervene on \( X \), we erase the arrow pointing into \( X \), set \( X \) to an arbitrary value, and propagate the new value along directed pathways.

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]
    \node[circle, draw] (X) {X};
    \node[circle, draw, right of=X] (Y) {Y};

    % Intervention on X
    \draw[dashed, ->] (X) -- node[above] {$a'$} (Y);

    % New value for X
    \node[circle, fill=gray!30, below left of=X, yshift=-1cm] (X_new) {X'}; 
    \draw[dashed, ->] (X_new) -- node[below] {$a'$} (Y);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

In this example:
- The dashed arrow from \( X' \) to \( Y \) indicates that \( Y \) changes due to the intervention.
- The original arrow from \( X \) to \( Y \) is replaced with a dashed arrow to show the new path

